# CSS Inheritance

## Definition

Inheritance is the mechanism by which some CSS properties automatically receive the value of their parent element.

## Example

```html
<div>
    <p>Hello World</p>
</div>
```

```css
div {
    color: blue;
}
```

Result:

```text
Hello World  → Blue
```

The `<p>` inherits the `color` from its parent `<div>`.

---

## Common Inherited Properties

### Text Properties
- `color`
- `text-align`
- `letter-spacing`
- `word-spacing`
- `line-height`

### Font Properties
- `font`
- `font-family`
- `font-size`
- `font-style`
- `font-weight`

### Other Properties
- `visibility`
- `cursor`

---

## Properties That Do NOT Inherit

- `margin`
- `padding`
- `border`
- `width`
- `height`
- `background`
- `background-color`
- `position`

Example:

```css
div {
    background-color: yellow;
}
```

The child element will **not** automatically get the yellow background.

---

## Force Inheritance

```css
p {
    color: inherit;
}
```

The child explicitly takes the parent's value.

---

## Example

```html
<div class="parent">
    <p>Paragraph</p>
</div>
```

```css
.parent {
    color: blue;
    font-size: 20px;
}
```

Result:

- Paragraph color → Blue
- Paragraph font size → 20px

Both values are inherited.

---

## Easy Memory Trick

### Usually Inherited
- Text
- Font
- Visibility

### Usually Not Inherited
- Box Model (margin, padding, border)
- Layout (width, height, position)
- Background

## One-Line Definition

**Inheritance** is the process by which child elements automatically receive certain CSS property values from their parent elements.
